The United States and Brazil have strengthened their science and technology partnership through various collaborations. These include cooperation in space weather, Earth observations, and the training of Brazilian scientists at the U.S. National Weather Service. The two countries are also working together on understanding the role of the tropics in the Earth's climate, advancing nanotechnology research, managing and monitoring natural disasters, refining measurement standards for biofuels, cultivating policies for innovation, enhancing public health, partnering for education and collaborative research, applying new technologies for the military, deepening their understanding of the Earth and space, advancing the cause of women in science, and improving transportation security. These collaborations aim to promote knowledge exchange, innovation, and economic strength between the two countries.